Lesson 1. Training the population in the field of protection from natural and man-made emergencies

1. Rights and responsibilities of citizens in the field of protection from emergency situations

In the event of an emergency, citizens of the Republic of Belarus have the right to protection of life and property; compensation and benefits; free medical care and free state social insurance; pension provision, etc.

In emergency situations, citizens of Belarus are required to know the methods, means of protection and techniques for providing first aid; comply with legislation in the field of protection from emergency situations; follow the established rules of conduct in the event of a threat or occurrence of emergency situations, etc.

Of great importance in the implementation of the rights and obligations of citizens are government bodies, in particular republican government bodies and other government organizations subordinate to the Council of Ministers of the Republic of Belarus.

Responsibilities of the republican government bodies and other state organizations subordinate to the Council of Ministers of the Republic of Belarus in the field of protecting the population and territories from emergency situations:

a) in relation to subordinate organizations:

  • develop and implement organizational and engineering measures to improve the sustainability of the industry in emergency situations;
  • approve and issue, in accordance with the requirements of the legislation of the Republic of Belarus, legal acts on the safety of production, technological processes, products, as well as the protection of employees of organizations from emergency situations;
  • ensure the development and implementation of measures to strengthen radiation, chemical, medical and biological, explosive, fire, and environmental safety;
  • finance and provide measures to prevent emergency situations and conduct emergency rescue and other urgent work in emergency situations;
  • organize and ensure the implementation of research, design, experimental design and testing work;

b) in relation to other organizations that are part of the industry:

  • provide methodological guidance in resolving issues related to protecting employees of organizations from emergency situations, increasing the sustainability and safety of the functioning of organizations;
  • develop and communicate to organizations industry requirements and legal acts on issues of preventing and eliminating emergency situations, and protecting employees of organizations from these situations.

2. Classification of natural emergencies, their sources, causes, brief description

In the Republic of Belarus, emergency situations are classified according to two main criteria:

1. Depending on the territorial distribution (local, regional, national and cross-border), the volume of material damage (from over forty basic units to over 0.5 million basic units), the number of affected people (from 10 to over 500 people)

2. By nature of origin (man-made, natural).

Man-made emergencies – transport accidents (disasters), fires, unprovoked explosions or their threat, accidents with the release (threat of release) of hazardous chemical, radioactive, biological substances, sudden destruction of structures and buildings, accidents on utility networks and life support structures, hydrodynamic accidents on dams, embankments and other engineering structures.

Natural emergencies are dangerous geological, meteorological, hydrological phenomena, degradation of soils or subsoil, natural fires, changes in the state of the air basin, infectious diseases of people and farm animals, mass damage to agricultural plants and forests by diseases or pests, changes in the state of water resources and the biosphere.

The classification of natural emergencies involves dividing emergencies into classes, groups and types (Table 1).

The causes of natural emergencies are characterized by natural and anthropogenic hazards.

Natural hazards include endogenous and exogenous processes.

  • Endogenous processes raise individual sections of the earth's crust. The main source of energy for endogenous processes is the internal heat in the bowels of the Earth. These processes cause volcanic activity, earthquakes, etc.
  • Exogenous processes destroy the earth's crust. Simultaneously with the destruction, there is a process of accumulation of destruction products. Exogenous natural disasters caused by solar energy and gravity (floods, storms, landslides, droughts, etc.)

Anthropogenic hazards. Thus, according to international statistics, about 80% of landslides are associated with human activity. As a result of deforestation, mudflow activity increases, and flood volumes increase. At present, the scale of use of natural resources has increased significantly, as a result, features of a global environmental crisis have become noticeably evident.

Natural emergencies in the Republic of Belarus. The most probable natural disasters in Belarus are: hydrological (floods), meteorological (strong winds, storms, hurricanes, heavy rainfall, hail, heavy snowfall, drought, frost), fires (forest fires, peat fires), geological (non-destructive and few earthquakes).

Infectious diseases occupy a special place among natural emergencies.

The danger of infectious diseases of people and animals (epidemics and epizootics). There are more than 500 natural foci of anthrax in the republic, there are natural foci of rabies, which can lead to mass diseases of domestic animals and people.

Damage to agricultural plants by diseases and pests (epiphytoties). Mass diseases of agricultural crops by brown rust and late blight are most common in the Brest, Grodno, and Gomel regions. The emergence of epizootic and epiphytotic foci on the territory of the republic may lead to a reduction in agricultural production by 5-10%.

3. Recommendations for citizens' actions in the event of a threat or occurrence of natural emergencies

Flood. When notified. A flood warning can be given by the signal "Attention everyone! " transmitted by ­sirens, intermittent horns of enterprises and vehicles. Having heard the signal, turn on the radio, TV and listen to the information and instructions for the population.

Upon receiving information about the start of the evacuation, you should quickly get ready and take with you: a bag with documents and money; a first aid ­kit; a three-day supply of food; bed linen and toiletries; a set of outerwear and shoes.

All evacuees must arrive at the evacuation point by the appointed time ­for registration and dispatch to a safe area. Depending on the current situation, the population is evacuated by specially designated transport or on foot.

Upon arrival at the final destination, registration takes place and transportation to temporary accommodation is organized ­.

In case of sudden flooding, it is recommended to occupy the nearest safe elevated place as quickly as possible ­and be prepared for an organized evacuation by water using various floating craft or on foot along fords. In such a situation, one should not give in to panic or lose self-control.

It is necessary to take measures to enable rescuers to promptly detect people cut off by water and in need of help. During daylight hours, this is achieved ­by hanging a white or colored cloth in a high place, and at night - by giving light signals.

Until help arrives, people in the flood zone should stay on the upper floors and roofs of buildings, trees and other elevated places. Usually, staying ­in the flood zone lasts until the water recedes or help arrives.

When in water Don't panic. Hold on to floating objects, try to tie them into a raft and climb onto it, push away dangerous objects with sharp protruding parts, try to swim to a safe place.

Hurricanes, storms, tornadoes. The main signs of the occurrence of hurricanes, storms and tornadoes are: an increase in wind speed and a sharp drop in atmospheric pressure; torrential rains and storm surges; violent snowfall and ground dust.

When warning. Information about the threat of hurricanes, storms and tornadoes carries information about the ­onset of a natural phenomenon in a specific area, the possible nature of its action and the behavior of people in the developing situation.

On the windward side of buildings, windows, doors, attic hatches and ventilation openings are tightly closed ­. Window and display glass is pasted over, protected with shutters or shields. To equalize the internal pressure, doors and windows on the leeward side of buildings are opened.

It is necessary to prepare electric ­lanterns, candles, camping stoves, food supplies, drinking water and medicines.

Upon receiving information about the immediate approach of a hurricane or severe storm, people take previously prepared places in buildings or shelters, and in In case of a tornado - only basements and underground structures.

In case of a sudden hurricane. When in a building, beware of injuries from shards of window glass. In case of strong gusts of wind, it is necessary to move away from windows and take a place in wall niches, doorways ­or stand close to the wall, and also use durable furniture and mattresses.

If you are forced to stay outdoors ­, it is advisable to move as far away from buildings as possible and take shelter in ravines, pits, ditches, canals, roadside ditches; in this case, you need to lie down in them and press yourself tightly to the ground. Such actions significantly reduce the number of injuries caused by the projectile action of hurricanes and storms, and also fully provide protection from flying shards of glass, bricks and other objects. It is not recommended to be on bridges, in places in close proximity to objects containing chemically hazardous and flammable substances. You can protect yourself from flying debris and shards of glass with plywood sheets, cardboard and plastic boxes, boards and other improvised means (Fig. 6).  

When hurricanes and storms are accompanied by thunderstorms, situations should be avoided in which ­the probability of electric shock increases. Therefore, one should not take shelter under isolated trees, poles and masts, or approach power transmission line supports too closely.

Lesson 2. Ensuring safety and the procedure for citizens to follow in the event of fires in buildings

1. The main causes of fires at industrial and civil facilities. Dangerous fire factors

It is considered a fire an uncontrolled fire outside a designated firebox that causes or may cause damage.

To fires in housing stock fires are related in residential premises intended or actually used for the residence of citizens, including fires in buildings and structures adjacent to them (bathhouses, sheds, garages, etc.).

The term “major fires” shall be understood as a fire, the damage from which amounts to 250 or more times the amount of the base value established on the day the fire occurred.

Damage caused by fires consists of the cost of destroyed or damaged fixed and working capital of organizations, unfinished capital construction and repair projects, and property of citizens.

Those killed in fires include persons who died at the scene of the incident or within seven days from the date of receiving bodily injuries from exposure to fire, high temperatures of combustion products and smoke, as a result of the collapse of structures and other dangerous factors of fire.

Conditions that promote fires in housing stock. The increase in the number of fires and other emergency situations at the present stage is objectively facilitated by a number of conditions associated with human life.

The housing stock is deteriorating, stove heating and electrical wiring are aging and not being updated for a long time, which is what causes their emergency condition. In 20-25% of cases, the cause of fires that occur in the housing stock are faulty electric heaters, electrical and gas household appliances that have exhausted their service life, and violation of the rules for their use.

Fire hazards (FH) - fire factors , the impact of which leads to injury , poisoning or death of a person, as well as to material damage . These include:

  • Flame, spark and high temperature. The combustion of all liquid, gaseous and most solid combustible substances that, when decomposing or evaporating, release gaseous products, is accompanied by the formation of a flame.

When technological installations burn, the intensity of heat radiation is so great that a person without special protective equipment cannot approach them closer than 10 m.

The flame temperature during combustion in air of some flammable substances is: wood - 850-1400°C, petroleum products in a tank - 1100-1300°C, carbon disulfide - 2195°C. At the same time, the temperature threshold for the viability of human tissue is 45°C.

Inhalation of heated air leads to damage and necrosis of the upper respiratory tract, suffocation and death of a person. When exposed to temperatures above 100°C, a person loses consciousness and dies within a few minutes.

Skin burns are dangerous for humans. The time it takes for a person to get second-degree burns is short: at an ambient temperature of 71°C - 26 sec, 15 sec. - at 100°C. Thus, a high ambient temperature is dangerous to human life not only in a burning room, but also in adjacent rooms where combustion products and heated air have entered.

  • Smoke. Smoke consists mainly of water vapor, gases formed during combustion, and many tiny solid unburned particles (coal, resinous products, etc.). Smoke is dangerous not only because of the toxic substances it contains, but also because it reduces visibility. Evacuation in such conditions becomes difficult or impossible.
  • Toxic combustion products. Combustion products often contain 50-100 types of chemical compounds that have a toxic effect - for example, when linoleum burns, hydrogen sulfide and sulfur dioxide are released; when upholstered furniture containing polyurethane foam burns, hydrogen cyanide is released. But the main cause of death in fires is carbon monoxide poisoning (CO). Carbon monoxide poisoning accounts for 18-25% of fatal intoxication cases.
  • One of the dangerous factors of a fire is a low oxygen content, since the combustion process occurs with intensive absorption of oxygen. Therefore, oxygen starvation may occur in fire conditions. Under normal conditions, a person breathes atmospheric air with an oxygen content of 20.9%. When the oxygen content in the air is 16-18%, there is an increased heart rate, a slight disorder of motor coordination, and a slight decrease in thinking ability. At 9% oxygen content in the breathing zone, loss of consciousness occurs, at 6% - death in minutes.

About 73% of those killed in fires die from exposure to toxic combustion products, about 20% from exposure to high temperatures, and about 5% from low oxygen levels. The rest die from injuries sustained as a result of collapsed building structures, flying debris from explosions, etc.

2. Procedure for actions of managers, officials, employees and citizens in the event of a fire in industrial and civil buildings

The main functions of the manager upon detection of a fire at a facility:

1. Reports an emergency to a higher authority, analyzes the situation, makes a decision.

2. Organizes the evacuation of people and material assets from the danger zone.

3. Manages fire extinguishing until emergency rescue units arrive.

The main functions of an employee upon detection of a fire at a facility:

1. Notifies the fire department and the facility manager about the fire.

2. Begins to extinguish the fire or leaves the danger zone if there is a threat to life and health.

Actions of a citizen who discovers a fire in a building:

1. Reports a fire to the fire department, alerts people and takes measures to evacuate them.

2. Takes measures to extinguish the fire.

Control over the current situation at the facility during a fire will depend not only on the manager or employee of the facility, but also on representatives of the volunteer fire brigade (VFB).

Correct actions of VFB representatives upon detection of a fire at a facility:

When a fire breaks out, the commander of a volunteer fire brigade takes measures to extinguish it, leads the volunteers and workers of the workshop, the section for extinguishing it, and, if necessary, gives the command to evacuate workers and employees. When the maximum permissible concentration of smoke is reached, he gives the command to evacuate the persons involved in localizing the fire.

Upon arrival, the shop manager, facility manager or fire service personnel report the situation and are placed at their disposal.

Vigilante №1. In case of a fire, notifies the fire department by calling 101 and notifies the management of the enterprise and the guard at the checkpoint. Meets the fire department and indicates the location of the fire. In the absence of the head of the VPD, performs his duties.

Vigilante №2. In the event of a fire, takes part in the evacuation of workers and employees, works with a fire nozzle from an internal fire hydrant, a fire extinguisher or other fire extinguishing means. In the absence of the head of the VFB, performs the duties of Vigilante №1.

Vigilantes №3 and №4. In case of fire, they ensure the evacuation of people from the premises. They extinguish the fire with the available fire extinguishing means. When the maximum smoke concentration is reached, they evacuate the building.

3. Features of behavior during a fire in multi-story buildings. Rules for evacuating people during a fire. Safety measures when in smoke-filled rooms

Signs of a fire starting. Most often, a fire in residential buildings starts with the appearance of a small flame, which is preceded by a more or less prolonged period of heating or smoldering of solid flammable objects, materials, substances.

The presence of a smell of overheated substance and the appearance of light, at first barely noticeable, and then increasingly thickening and affecting the eyes smoke are the first sure signs of a fire. Electric wires, gradually heating up when overloaded, first signal this with a characteristic smell of rubber, and then the insulation ignites and burns or smolders, setting fire to nearby objects, wooden building structures.

Along with the smell of rubber, the light may go out or the electric lamps may begin to glow dimly, which is sometimes also a sign of impending ignition of the insulation of electrical wires.

When the room where the fire started has increased ventilation (open window, door to the balcony), people in the neighboring rooms sometimes learn about the fire not by smoke or the smell of burning, but by the crackling of burning wood. Sometimes a whistling sound is heard, and flame reflections may be visible.

What to do if you are caught in a fire in a multi-story building (apartment building, hotel, etc.) First of all, when entering any unfamiliar building, try to remember your way, pay attention to the location of the main and emergency exits.

1. If you hear cries of “Fire!” or smell smoke, or see flames, call the Ministry of Emergency Situations on duty at “101”.

2. Try to stay calm and calm the people around you. Find out where it is coming from, then start moving towards the exit. When moving in a crowd, let children, women and the elderly go first. Help those who are paralyzed by fear and cannot move, talk to them calmly and clearly, support them by the arms.

3. When you find yourself in a crowd, bend your elbows and press them to your sides, clenching your fists. Lean your body back, pushing your feet forward, and try to hold back the pressure with your back, freeing up space in front and moving slowly. Shield children with your back or sit them on your shoulders.

4. Do not enter where there is a high concentration of smoke! Modern buildings contain a lot of plastic and synthetics, which emit highly toxic substances when burning. A few breaths can lead to death.

5. When rooms and corridors are filled with smoke, go towards the smoke-free staircase or the exit, but not towards the elevator. Hold on to the walls, handrails, breathe through a handkerchief or clothing. If the concentration of smoke increases, bend down or crawl.

6. If you cannot go out onto the stairs or into the hallway due to thick smoke, high temperatures and fire, you must immediately return back, closing the door tightly behind you. And plug the cracks and ventilation holes with wet rags. Create a supply of water in the bathroom.

7. If a dangerous concentration of smoke and elevated temperature is formed in the apartment (room), you should go out onto the balcony or loggia, closing the door tightly. Take a wet blanket, carpet, or other thick fabric with you to cover yourself from the fire if it penetrates through the door or window openings.

8. If it is dangerous to remain in the room or on the balcony, try to go down to the floor below, using tightly tied sheets, curtains, ropes, etc. You can also use a fire hose for self-rescue. We recommend rescuing one at a time, backing each other up.

9. If you decide to escape through a heavily smoke-filled corridor, which is extremely dangerous, we advise you to take a wet thick cloth, which you should cover yourself with, and move bent over or crawling. If a shaft of fire is approaching you, then, without delay, fall, covering your head with a cloth, at this moment do not breathe, so as not to get burns to your internal organs.

4. Purpose of technical means of fire protection. Primary fire extinguishing means

Technical fire protection equipment is used in cases where, due to production technology conditions, it is impossible to exclude the possibility of contact between flammable substances and potential ignition sources.

One of the most important components of technical fire protection equipment is primary fire extinguishing equipment.

Primary fire extinguishing means are intended to eliminate small fires and fires at an early stage by the personnel of the facility, without waiting for the arrival of emergency rescue units of the Ministry of Emergency Situations. Such means include fire extinguishers, fire equipment (fire buckets, boxes with sand, shovels, fire blankets, barrels with water, etc.) and fire tools (crowbars, axes, etc.).

The most effective primary fire extinguishing agent is a fire extinguisher. Portable fire extinguishers (carbon dioxide, powder, air-foam) with a body volume of 5 to 100 liters can be used as primary fire extinguishing means at facilities.

In Belarus, carbon dioxide and powder fire extinguishers are mostly used. In residential buildings, offices, archives and premises where computers, office equipment and other valuable equipment are located, carbon dioxide fire extinguishers are often used (fig. 7).

Fig. 7. Carbon dioxide fire extinguisher

Powder fire extinguishers are suitable for use in production, storage facilities, garages and cars. They are very effective in extinguishing flammable liquids and gases. Despite the widespread use of powder fire extinguishers, some of them (powder fire extinguishers with gas-generating devices) pose a serious danger to humans and are prohibited by the legislation of the Republic of Belarus.

There are general rules for using a fire extinguishers:

1. First, prepare the device for operation - break the seal and pull out the pin. The fire extinguisher is triggered when you press the lever.

2. To avoid fire from getting on you, stand on the side from which the wind is blowing. This will also help you avoid inhaling harmful substances that are present in the contents of the fire extinguisher.

3. The stream should be directed at the base of the burning surface, not at the flame itself. This rule does not include cases where the fire has started in a niche - the stream should be directed from top to bottom. As for the burning vertical surface, it should be extinguished from the bottom up.

4. If there are several fire extinguishers, it is better to use them all at once. To do this, you need to involve people nearby.

5. When finished, make sure that the flame has gone out completely and there are no more ignition sources.

to the fire department immediately after use. reloading.



Fig. 9. Rules for using a fire extinguisher

When working with a fire extinguisher, it is important to remember the following:

  1. If a powder fire extinguisher is used in a closed and small space, it is necessary to ventilate the room immediately after stopping extinguishing, as the powder irritates the respiratory system.
  2. When using a carbon dioxide fire extinguisher, it is forbidden to hold the bell, as it cools down very much, which can lead to frostbite of the hands. Also, using a carbon dioxide fire extinguisher in closed rooms with a small volume is dangerous due to carbon dioxide poisoning, so after extinguishing the fire, you must leave the room and take measures to ventilate it.
  3. Carbon dioxide and powder fire extinguishers, after being activated, must not be turned into a horizontal position - they must be oriented vertically, otherwise their efficiency will be minimal (zero).

Lesson №3. Ensuring the safety of passenger transportation services on public transport and the procedure for passengers to follow in the event of dangerous incidents

1. Legislation of the Republic of Belarus in the field of organizing safe transportation of passengers by public transport. Rights and obligations of the driver and passenger of public transport.

Currently, in Belarus, there are a number of legal acts that determine the safe transportation of passengers on transport:

1. Law of the Republic of Belarus of August 14, 2007 №278-3 "On Automobile Transport and Automobile Transportation" with amendments for 2022.

2. Resolution of the Council of Ministers of the Republic of Belarus of June 30, 2008 №972 “On certain issues of automobile transportation of passengers”.

3. Law of the Republic of Belarus of May 5, 2014 №141-3 “On urban electric transport and metro”.

4. Resolution of the Council of Ministers of the Republic of Belarus of November 22, 2014 №1088 “On approval of the Rules for the transportation of passengers by urban electric transport and the Rules for the transportation of passengers by metro”.

Urban electric transport (trolleybus, tram).

The driver has the right:

  • make proposals on improving the transportation of passengers by urban electric transport and the work of dispatch stations, improving the quality of passenger service, the safety of passenger transportation by urban electric transport, improving the working hours and rest time of drivers, and the efficient use of vehicles;
  • control the payment of travel;
  • appeal in the prescribed manner against illegal actions of controlling persons.

Driver is obliged to:

  • know and comply with these Rules, the Road Traffic Regulations, the rules for labor protection and fire safety, the rules for technical operation and safety of trolleybuses or trams;
  • undergo a medical examination in the prescribed manner before the flight and, if necessary, during or after the flight, which must be noted in the waybill or other transport document;
  • check the technical condition of the vehicle before and during work in accordance with the requirements of the driver's manual;
  • carry out the boarding and disembarking of passengers after the trolleybus or tram has come to a complete stop within the area of the stopping point;
  • warn passengers about closing vehicle doors;
  • check that the vehicle doors are closed before starting to move;
  • know the location of dangerous areas along the route, technical and medical assistance points;
  • stop transporting passengers and the independent movement of the trolleybus if a current leakage exceeding the permissible limit is detected on the trolleybus body;
  • provide first aid to the passenger if necessary, or call an ambulance, or take measures to deliver the passenger to the nearest medical facility;
  • comply with the requirements for the working hours and rest time of drivers.

The passenger has the right:

  • purchase a travel document and travel on public electric transport;
  • enjoy discounted fares;
  • receive timely and accurate information about the schedule of urban electric transport, fares and other conditions for transporting passengers by urban electric transport;
  • receive compensation in accordance with the law for harm caused to his life, health or property.

The passenger is obliged to:

  • give up specially designated seats to passengers with preschool-age children, pregnant women, disabled people and elderly citizens;
  • hold on to the handrail while driving while standing in the car, being careful;
  • do not lean on the vehicle doors;
  • do not transport substances and objects prohibited for transportation;
  • do not smoke or drink alcohol in the vehicle;
  • do not use open flames inside the vehicle;
  • do not lean out of the vehicle's window openings;
  • do not distract the driver from driving the vehicle and do not interfere with him while driving;
  • do not throw things or objects out of vehicle windows;
  • do not use aerosols in the vehicle interior;
  • not to create inconvenience to other passengers, the driver, conductor and controlling persons by their actions, condition and behavior;
  • compensate the carrier or other passengers in accordance with the procedure established by law for damage caused by careless or intentional actions.

Fire safety systems in public transport. Organizational and technical measures, automatic fire extinguishing systems. The safety of passenger transportation in public transport depends not only on the duties of the driver, passenger, requirements for the technical condition of vehicles, but also on fire safety systems. Currently, the most important element of fire safety is the automatic fire extinguishing system. Automatic fire extinguishing system includes the following elements : automatic fire extinguishing system, automatic fire alarm, warning and evacuation control system .

Automatic fire extinguishing system (AFES) is a fire extinguishing system that is automatically activated when fire factors exceed threshold values in the protected area. A distinctive feature of automatic systems is that they also perform automatic fire alarm functions. There are several types of AFES. Aerosol and foam automatic fire extinguishing systems are recommended for localizing and extinguishing fires in transport.

Liability for violation of fire safety rules in transport. Violation of fire safety rules in railway, automobile, water or air transport, urban electric transport (in the subway, tram, trolleybus), highways and road structures - entails the imposition of a fine of up to twenty basic units.

2. Procedure for passengers of public urban transport (tram, trolleybus, bus) in case of an accident. Recommendations for actions of citizens in case of fire, in public urban automobile and electric transport

Accidents on public transport (bus, trolleybus, tram, metro) occur much less frequently than on automobile transport, but even here emergency situations may arise involving human casualties and material damage.

The procedure for passengers in case of accidents on public transport (collision, rollover) (fig. 10):

  1. It is necessary to take a stable position and firmly grasp the handrails (belts) with your hands; the seated passenger should rest his feet on the floor, his hands on the front seat (panel) and tilt his head forward.
  2. The accident happens quickly, after the accident a rollover and overturning are possible. You must not relax and keep all your muscles tense until it becomes absolutely clear that there will be no more movement.
  3. After the impact has occurred, the first thing you need to do is determine where and in what place in the vehicle, and in what position you are, whether there is a fire, whether gasoline is leaking (especially in the event of a rollover). Depending on the situation, move to the exit - through the door or window. If there are a lot of people in the vehicle, it is wiser to use emergency exits in addition to the doors and windows. You can get out by breaking the window glass. However, glass can be strong and you should find suitable improvised means to break it. Having broken the glass, do not forget about the fragments - in a panic you can seriously injure yourself.
  4. Once outside, immediately get involved in rescue operations: if necessary, help passengers break glass, pull out victims, provide first aid, etc.

Fig. 10. Measures to take in case of an accident on public transport

Recommendations for citizens’ actions in the event of a fire in public transport:

  1. Immediately report the appearance of smoke or fire to the driver. Try to open the doors (use the emergency opening button).

If the doors are blocked, use the emergency hatches in the roof and the side windows for evacuation. If necessary, knock out the windows with both feet (or a hard object). If you have successfully freed yourself without serious injuries, then, as far as possible, help those remaining, especially children and the elderly.

  1. Any vehicle contains materials that emit toxic gases when burning, so leave the vehicle quickly, covering your mouth and nose with a handkerchief or sleeve.
  2. Try using a fire extinguisher and improvised means to put out the fire. BE CAREFUL! In trolleybuses and trams, metal parts may become energized as a result of the protective insulation of the wires burning.
  3. Leave the vehicle, letting children, women and the elderly go first. Once you get out of the vehicle, move away as far as possible, as fuel tanks may explode or a short circuit may occur in the high-voltage electrical network.
  4. Report the fire by phone or through drivers of passing cars. Call the Ministry of Emergency Situations on duty at 101. Provide assistance to the victims.

The order of actions for passengers in case of a fire in the metro:

1. If you smell smoke, immediately inform the driver about the fire via the intercom.

2. If an open fire appears in the carriage while the train is moving, try to put it out using the fire extinguishers under the seats or improvised means. If possible, move to the part of the carriage not occupied by the fire (preferably forward) and contain the spread of the fire by knocking down the flames with clothing or pouring any non-flammable liquids (water, milk, etc.) on them. Never try to stop the train in a tunnel with the emergency stopcock - this will make it more difficult to put out the fire and evacuate you.

3. In case of heavy smoke, close your eyes and breathe through a damp handkerchief, respirator or gas mask.

4. In case of a major fire in the carriage itself, break the window at the end of the carriage and move to the next one, provide assistance to children and the elderly.

5. After arriving at the station and opening the doors, let children and the elderly go first. Check if anyone is left in the carriage, help these people to leave it. Immediately report the fire to the station duty officer and the escalator.

When a train stops in a tunnel, do not attempt to leave it without the driver's command; do not touch the metal body of the car or the doors until the high voltage has been switched off throughout the entire section.

After permission to exit, open the doors or kick out the windows, exit the carriage and move forward in the direction of the train to the station. Walk along the track between the rails in single file, without touching the current-carrying buses (on the side of the rails) to avoid electric shock when the voltage is turned on. Be especially careful when exiting the tunnel near the station, at the intersections of tracks, at switches, as an oncoming train may appear.

If the train you left behind has moved and is catching up with you, press yourself against the niche of the tunnel wall. Immediately inform the station attendant about what happened and follow his instructions.

3. Procedure for passengers in case of fire in a railway carriage. Emergency safety measures in case of dangerous incidents on water and air transport

In case of fire on the train:

1. Immediately inform the conductor about the fire, walk through the carriage and announce the incident to the passengers. Wake up sleeping passengers. The safest way is to evacuate to the front carriages, but if this is not possible, then go to the end of the train, tightly closing the doors of the compartments and inter-carriage passages behind you.

2. Using fire extinguishers and improvised means (blankets, wet rags, etc.), try to put out the fire together with the passengers. Close the windows so that the wind does not fan the flames. Do not try to save your luggage from the fire if this threatens your safety (take only the most necessary things - documents, money, valuables, etc.).

If the fire has cut you off from the exits, then enter the compartment or toilet, close the door tightly behind you, open the window and wait for help to arrive, attracting attention to yourself. Do not jump out of the carriage of a moving train and do not try to get out onto the roof. Jump out of the carriage only as a last resort, putting on more clothes for cushioning and using a mattress.

3. If it is impossible to extinguish the fire and contact the train conductor or the driver, stop the train using the emergency brake, remove all people from the car by opening the doors or breaking the windows. Take passengers away from the burning car and send people to the nearest populated area to report the incident to the fire department.

Emergency safety measures in case of dangerous incidents on water transport. What to do if the vessel is sinking:

1. Follow all instructions from the captain clearly and quickly.

2. Put on life jackets for yourself and your loved ones, remove any tight clothing and shoes. Take your documents with you (under your underwear), having previously wrapped them in a plastic bag.

3. Quickly, but without undue haste, go up on deck and, at the captain’s command, board the boats (rafts) one by one, letting children and women go first;

4. If it is impossible to get into the boat, take any floating object with you (a ring, a board, an empty plastic bottle with a closed cap, etc.) and, after looking around, jump into the water feet first.

5. Once in the water, swim 200-300 m away from the side of the ship to avoid being pulled under the water or under the bottom of the ship.

If possible, help people nearby stay afloat. Try to form a group to help each other and organize joint rescue efforts.

When you see a boat with free space, swim up to it from the stern, do not lean on the side. If there is no space in the boat, ask to throw you a rope (cable, rope), tie it around your waist and swim to the shore behind the boat.

Save your strength and monitor the blood circulation in your hands and feet (to restore blood circulation, do a massage). If you are very thirsty, put a wet handkerchief on your head and wipe your body with it.

Emergency safety measures in case of dangerous incidents in air transport. Actions in case of a fire that occurs during landing of an aircraft:

1. Observe all instructions prescribed by the flight rules.

2. Protect exposed ­areas of the body from direct exposure to fire by using available clothing, blankets, etc. Breathe only through cotton or woolen clothing, if possible moistened with water.

3. After the plane lands and stops, immediately head to the nearest exit. In a smoke-filled airplane cabin, it is better to crawl or crawl to the exit, as there is less smoke below.

4. If the passage is blocked, make your way through the chairs, lowering their backs.

5. After ­exiting the plane, move as far away from it as possible and lie down on the ground, pressing your head with your hands - there is a possibility of an explosion.

Factors that contribute to the emergence of panic, ways and means of its termination. Prevention of panic among passengers on public transport. Panic is a state of mass fear in the presence of an obvious or imaginary threat.

The following factors contribute to the emergence of panic:

1. Limiting the space in which events develop (or developed), especially if the exit is difficult.

2. Real concerns, difficult to accurately assess, of a large number of people for their own health and lives.

3. The presence of a certain “emotional orientation” of the masses that is conducive to panic, which is expressed in general excitement, anxiety, and which can be intensified not only by a real threat, but also by rumors.

4. Lack of confidence in the competence of the forces called upon to maintain public order during disasters, which greatly complicates rescue operations.

To prevent panic, it is necessary to tell people the whole truth about what happened from the very beginning of the emergency. Information should be repeated periodically, increased. It is necessary not only to talk about the course of rescue operations and give explanations, but also to make requests to them, to involve them in the common cause of eliminating the consequences of a natural disaster or accident. Each person should feel involved in these important events.

What to do if panic does arise? It should be stopped immediately and decisively. And preferably as early as possible, when it is superficial, has not affected large masses and can be quickly eliminated.

To do this, first of all, it is necessary to distract people's attention from the source of fear or panic-causing agent, at least for a short time. Give people the opportunity to wake up from fear, at least for a moment, and try to take control of the crowd. Try to switch people's attention from the actions of the panic-mongering "leader" to a person who thinks soberly and has a cool head. Here, there should be a place for powerful and loud commands from people with a strong character.

Usually, when the initial feeling of fear passes, most people in such a situation experience increased activity, a desire to somehow make amends for their guilt. This should be used to involve everyone in rescue work, assigning each a specific area.

If panic has nevertheless taken hold of a significant number of people, they must be divided into smaller groups, each of which will be much easier to deal with.

Lesson #4. Conditions requiring first aid. Respiratory and circulatory arrest, measures to revive the body

1. Definition of the concept of "first aid". General principles of providing first aid to victims in emergency situations.

First aid is a set of simple measures carried out directly at the site of injury or near it as a form of self- and mutual assistance, as well as by participants in emergency rescue operations using standard and improvised means.

When providing first aid, the following principles should be followed:

  1. Correctness and appropriateness
  2. Speed and care
  3. Determination and calmness.

First aid measures:

  • performing cardiopulmonary resuscitation;
  • temporary stopping of external bleeding;
  • anesthesia;
  • immobilization of damaged limbs;
  • application of aseptic dressings to wounds.

Assessing the condition of the victim is an assessment of the vital functions of the body (Fig. 14).

Fig. 14. Evaluation of vital signs of the victim's body

The procedure for assessing consciousness:

1. Approach the victim.

2. Holding his head in place with your hand, shake him by the shoulder.

3. Ask questions: Do you need help? Can you hear me? What happened? What hurts?

Algorithm for determining the state of consciousness:

A – Alert - consciousness preserved

V – Voice - responds to voice

P – Pain - reacts to pain

U – Unresponsive - no reaction

To carry out a breathing assessment it is necessary:

1. Listen to the breathing at the mouth.

2. Check for respiratory movements of the chest and abdomen.

To assess blood circulation, it is necessary to feel the pulse in the carotid artery.

2. List of conditions requiring first aid.

The concept of clinical death

At present, it can be considered established that death (dying) is not only a qualitative “leap” from the living state of an organism to the dead, but also a more or less prolonged biological process consisting of several phases.

The following medical and biological phases are distinguished, which were one of the first to be described by the prominent Russian resuscitation physician, academician V. A. Negovsky :

1) pre-mortem, or pre-agonistic , phase;

2) terminal stop phase;

3) the agony phase;

4) clinical death;

5) biological death.

The pre-death or pre-agonic phase may have different durations in different cases. If, for example, as a result of an electric shock the work of the human heart immediately stops, then the pre-death phase is practically absent.

In many other cases, when a person dies due to bleeding, traumatic shock, or lung failure, this phase can take several hours.

Transition from the dying stage ( pre-agonistic ) phases to agony occurs through a very short phase called terminal arrest: the dying person's breathing stops and reflexes fade. The terminal arrest phase lasts from five seconds to four minutes.

After the terminal stop comes agony , at the beginning of which there is usually an increase in all weakened, "extinguished" functions of the body. Some researchers believe that the brain of a dying person, making a final effort, mobilizes its capabilities, so consciousness, thinking, memory and other cognitive processes return to it, becoming "brighter" than usual.

Already in the agony phase, when the heart and respiratory system are still working, the patient loses consciousness. In an unconscious state, the dying person no longer reacts even to strong stimuli. In this state, the patient makes chaotic and automated movements (periodically hits himself on the chest and stomach, bends the edge of the sheet with his fingers, etc.), since only the subcortical formations and the vital centers of the medulla oblongata, freed from the control of the cortex, act in him, and this is in conditions of deepening oxygen starvation.

During the agony phase, the activity of the medulla oblongata is preserved, and as a result, so is the breathing and work of the cardiovascular system of the dying person. As a result of overstimulation of the respiratory center of the brain located here, the breathing of the dying person becomes deep and spasmodic.

As oxygen starvation deepens further, the hyperactivity of the medulla oblongata is replaced by inhibition, and after some time breathing stops.

During the agony, the heart's function is also disrupted, and eventually it stops beating.

Thus, the phase of clinical death begins from the moment when the work of the heart and respiratory system stops. The duration of this phase, if we average the estimates of different authors, is 4-7 minutes. This is a short phase between life and death .

However, there are significant individual differences in the duration of the clinical phase and the rate of death among people, so resuscitation efforts should be started even in cases where more time than the specified 4–7 minutes has passed since the onset of the clinical death phase.

Many facts show that the clinical phase in children reaches 8-10 minutes and more. In some cases, even children who were in the clinical phase for up to 25-30 minutes were saved. In any case, when healthy children, as a result of accidents, find themselves in the phase of clinical death, then this phase takes them much longer than in elderly and sick people.

The last (final) stage of the existence of a once living organism is considered to be biological death, in which irreversible changes and complete cessation of all life processes occur. Its signs are: the appearance of hypostatic (cadaveric) spots, a cold body, rigor mortis.

3. Sequence of measures to revive the body. Measures to restore and maintain airway patency. Artificial respiration using the mouth-to-mouth method, closed cardiac massage

Resuscitation (from lat. re — prefix expressing: renewal, repetition + lat. animator — life-giving ), a set of measures to revive a person in a state clinical death .

In a medical sense, resuscitation may include cardiopulmonary resuscitation (Fig.15) , intensive therapy and a range of measures aimed at maintaining life.

Before starting resuscitation measures, it is necessary to lay the victim on a hard surface, unbutton his clothes as much as possible, and loosen his tie and belt.

Fig. 15. Stages of cardiopulmonary resuscitation

Stage C. Carrying out closed (indirect) cardiac massage.

Conditions for performing closed cardiac massage (Fig. 16):

1. Pressure is applied to the sternum 2-3 cm above the xiphoid process.

2. The depth of the sternum bend is 4 cm.

3. The frequency of chest compressions is 90-100 per minute.

The ventilation-massage ratio is 2:30.

Fig. 16. Closed cardiac massage

It is generally accepted that the basis of indirect cardiac massage is the compression of the heart from the front by the sternum, from behind - by the spinal column, as a result of which blood from the heart cavities enters the vessels of the body. This is the so-called cardiac pump . But during indirect cardiac massage, not only the heart is compressed, but also other intrathoracic structures (the most important is the compression of the lungs, which contain a significant amount of blood and are easily compressed). This mechanism is commonly called the chest pump .

During closed cardiac massage, both mechanisms work in a person, but the chest pump predominates, when, when the chest is compressed, the movement of blood into the aorta is ensured by the compression of all vascular capacities. The main capacity is the lungs with their pulmonary circulation.

Stage A. Ensuring airway patency:

This is the first resuscitation measure, which largely ensures the success of the entire cardiopulmonary resuscitation. The causes of airway obstruction are tongue retraction, obstruction by foreign bodies (blood, vomit, mucus, laryngospasm, bronchospasm). The most common cause is tongue retraction to the back wall of the pharynx in an unconscious patient . This is explained by the inevitable loss of tone in the muscles of the lower jaw and neck, which raise the root of the tongue above the back wall of the pharynx. Thus, the tongue, due to its own weight, retracts to the back wall of the pharynx and acts as a valve during inhalation, preventing the flow of air.

Airway obstruction can be partial or complete.

In case of partial obstruction, noisy breathing is heard, and accessory muscles (retraction of intercostal spaces, neck muscles) participate in the act of breathing.

An attempt to place a pillow under the patient's head leads to the transition of partial obstruction to complete (Fig. 17). With complete obstruction of the airways, active but unsuccessful attempts to inhale are noted, which after a few minutes are replaced by respiratory arrest, and then cardiac arrest.

Fig. 17. Obturation of the airways with the tongue

Thus, obstruction of the airways, regardless of the degree of obstruction and the cause that caused it, can cause the death of the patient.

The main method of opening the airways is the triple Safar airway maneuver, which consists of tilting the head back, pushing the lower jaw forward, and opening the mouth (Fig. 18).

Fig. 18. Restoring airway patency

After performing the triple Safar maneuver on the airways (it takes a few seconds to perform), it is necessary to take 3-5 breaths into the victim's lungs. If the chest does not inflate, one can suspect obstruction of the airways by a foreign body.

Foreign substances can be removed with the fingers (Fig. 19). To do this, insert the index finger deep into the pharynx to the base of the tongue, trying to use the finger, like a hook, to remove the foreign body. It is important not to push it further into the respiratory tract. You can use the index and middle fingers for this purpose, manipulating them like tweezers.

Fig. 19. Removal of foreign bodies from the oral cavity

Stage B. Performing artificial respiration. There are two main methods of artificial respiration : mouth-to-mouth and mouth-to-nose (Fig. 20).

The mouth-to-mouth method. The essence of the method is that the person providing assistance blows air from his lungs into the victim's lungs through his mouth. Artificial respiration "mouth-to-mouth" is more rational than other methods of artificial ventilation of the lungs, since the exhaled air of a healthy person contains 4% carbon dioxide, which is a stimulant of the respiratory center of the victim's brain, and 16% oxygen, sufficient to maintain his life. In addition, atmospheric air, located in the upper respiratory tract and containing 21% oxygen, joins the exhaled air.

Artificial respiration "from mouth to mouth" is dangerous due to infection, therefore artificial ventilation of the lungs must be carried out using gauze, a napkin or a handkerchief.

Artificial mouth-to-nose breathing It is performed if the victim has clenched teeth or has an injury to the lips or jaws. 

When performing artificial respiration, it is important to remember that the blowing should be quick and sharp.

Fig. 20. Methods of artificial ventilation of the lungs

Lesson 5. First aid for electric shock, lightning, flame burns, frostbite, drowning

1. The effect of electric current on the human body. The sequence and content of measures to provide first aid

The dangerous and harmful effects of electric current on people are manifested in the form of electrical injuries . Electrical injuries are injuries caused by the impact of electric current on the body, which are conventionally divided into general (electric shock), local and mixed.

The concept of electric shock. Electric shock is understood as damage to living tissues of the body by an electric current flowing through it, manifested in involuntary convulsive contractions of various muscles of the body. In the case of electric shock, the entire body is at risk of damage due to the disruption of the normal functioning of its various organs and systems, including the heart, lungs, central nervous system, etc. 

Depending on the outcome of the injury, electric shocks can be conditionally divided into the following five degrees:
I - convulsive, barely perceptible muscle contraction;

II – convulsive contraction of muscles, accompanied by severe, barely bearable pain, without loss of consciousness;

III – convulsive contraction of muscles with loss of consciousness, but with preserved breathing and heart function;

IV – loss of consciousness and disruption of cardiac activity or breathing;
V – clinical death, i.e. absence of breathing and blood circulation.

Local damage caused by exposure to electric current. Typical local electrical injuries include electrical burns, electrical signs, skin metallization, mechanical damage, and electro-ophthalmia .

Electrical burns, which occur as a result of heat being released when current passes through the human body, are the most common electrical injury. Depending on the conditions of occurrence, there are two main types of burns: current (or contact) and arc.

An electric burn occurs when current passes directly through the human body as a result of contact with a live part. This type of burn is usually a skin burn at the point of contact of the body with the live part. An electric burn occurs when contacting an electrical installation with a relatively low voltage – no higher than 1000-2000 V and is usually characterized by I or II degree (reddening of the skin, formation of blisters); sometimes severe burns of III and IV degrees occur ( at voltages higher than 380 V) .

An arc burn is the result of the impact of an electric arc on the body, which has a high temperature (over 3500° C) and high energy. This burn usually occurs upon contact with a high-voltage electrical installation - over 1000 V and, as a rule, is severe - III or IV degree (necrosis of the entire thickness of the skin, charring of tissue, etc.). An electric arc can cause extensive burns of the body, burning of tissue to a great depth, charring and traceless burning of large areas of the body.

Electric sign – this is a specific skin lesion, expressed in necrosis of the affected areas. Electrical marks are clearly defined spots of gray or pale yellow color. Often the marks are round or oval in shape and 1-5 mm in size. The surface of the mark is dry and not inflamed. The affected area of skin hardens like a callus. As a rule, electrical marks are painless and their treatment ends successfully.

Metallization of the skin is the penetration of tiny metal particles into the skin under the influence of electric current. The affected area of the skin has a rough and hard surface, the color of which is determined by the color of the metal compounds that have penetrated the skin: green - upon contact with copper, gray - with aluminum, yellow-gray - with lead. The affected area experiences pain from the burn and the presence of foreign bodies. Over time, the diseased skin acquires a normal appearance and the painful sensations disappear. Only if the eyes are affected can the treatment be long and complicated, and in some cases, ineffective. Usually exposed parts of the body are affected – hands and face.

Mechanical damage occurs under the influence of current, involuntary convulsive contraction of muscles. This can lead to rupture of skin, blood vessels and nerve tissue. Mechanical damage occurs when working mainly in installations up to 1000 V with a relatively long stay of a person under voltage. Mechanical damage occurs quite rarely and requires long-term treatment. Such damage is always accompanied by electric shocks. Some of them are also accompanied by contact burns of the body. 

Electrophthalmia is a lesion of the outer membranes of the eyes due to exposure to ultraviolet radiation from an electric arc. Electrophthalmia develops 4-8 hours after ultraviolet irradiation. In this case, there is redness and inflammation of the skin and mucous membranes of the eyelids, lacrimation, purulent discharge from the eyes, eyelid spasms and partial blindness. The disease usually lasts for several days. In case of damage to the cornea, treatment is more complex and lengthy. The electric arc creates a strong light radiation (brighter than Sun ), therefore, for example, welders use special glasses with dark glass to protect the eyes.

Factors affecting the outcome of electric shock:

1. Passage of current through the human body. The path of current in the human body depends on which parts of the body the victim touches the live parts. The path of electric current through the human body is called a loop. The most dangerous type is a complete loop, which connects four limbs and affects all internal organs (Fig. 21). 

Fig. 21. Complete ( W -shaped) current flow loop

2. Resistance of human tissues. Different tissues of the body provide different resistance to current. Thus, bones, cartilage, ligaments and skin provide high resistance to current. Muscles and blood provide comparatively low resistance.

Methods of freeing a victim from the effects of electric current, personal safety measures. The first action that must be taken when a person is exposed to electric current is to turn off the electrical installation that is under voltage. However, in the conditions of large industrial enterprises, this is not always possible. Then it is necessary to cut or chop the wire or cable with an axe with a dry wooden handle, or to pull the victim away from the source of current. 

To separate the victim from live parts or wires, use dry clothing, a stick, a board or any other dry object that does not conduct electric current. The use of metal or wet objects for these purposes is not allowed.

To separate the victim from live parts, you can also grab his clothes (if they are dry and do not come away from the victim's body), while avoiding touching surrounding metal objects and body parts not covered by clothing.

When pulling the victim by the legs, do not touch his shoes or clothes without properly insulating your hands, as shoes and clothes may be damp and conduct electric current.

To isolate the hands, the person providing assistance, especially if it is necessary to touch the body of the victim who is not covered by clothing, should wrap his hands with a scarf, put a cloth cap on his hands, use rubberized material (raincoat) or just dry material.

If the victim touches a torn high-voltage line wire, and the wire is lying on the ground, then before approaching the victim, it is necessary to place a dry board, a bundle of dry clothes under his feet and separate the wire from the victim using a dry board or a stick. When separating the victim from live parts, it is recommended to act with one hand if possible.

If it is not possible to separate the victim from the live parts, then the wires should be cut or severed. You can use an axe if its handle is absolutely dry. You need to cut the wires (each one separately), placing the same board under them.

In addition, the wires (each one separately) can be cut with pliers or nippers with insulated handles; in extreme cases, you can use a tool with metal handles, but wrap them in dry woolen or rubberized material.

Failure to cut the wires individually may result in a short circuit. The resulting arc can cause severe burns to the body and eye damage to the person providing the aid.

If a person is exposed to voltage above 1000 V, such precautions are not sufficient. It is necessary to contact specialists who will immediately remove the voltage.

Sequence and content of first aid measures. First aid measures depend on the condition of the victim after being released from the effects of electric current.

If the victim is conscious but has previously fainted, he should be placed in a comfortable position (put something underneath him and cover him with some clothing) and ensure complete rest until the doctor arrives, continuously monitoring his breathing and pulse. It is prohibited to allow the victim to move, much less continue working, since the absence of symptoms after electric shock does not exclude the possibility of subsequent deterioration of the victim's condition. If it is not possible to quickly call a doctor, it is necessary to urgently deliver the victim to a medical facility, providing the necessary transport or stretcher for this.

If the victim is unconscious, but with stable breathing and pulse, he should be laid flat and comfortably, unbuttoned, create an influx of fresh air, give him ammonia to smell, spray his face with water and provide complete rest. If the victim is breathing poorly - very rarely and convulsively (like a dying person), he should be given artificial respiration and indirect (external) heart massage.

If the victim shows no signs of life (breathing and pulse), he cannot be considered dead, since death is often only apparent. In such a state, the victim will actually die if he is not given immediate first aid in the form of artificial respiration and external (indirect) cardiac massage. Artificial respiration should be performed continuously, both before and after the doctor arrives. The question of the advisability or futility of further artificial respiration is decided by the doctor.

2. Flame burns, sequence and content of first aid measures. Frostbite, first aid measures (by stages)

Flame, acting on tissue, causes moisture to evaporate and protein to coagulate. With prolonged exposure to it, the skin contracts, stretches, ­and breaks, forming cracks and ruptures resembling cut wounds.

During primary wound treatment, it is difficult to remove the remains of burnt clothing; unnoticed threads of fabric may subsequently serve as foci of infection. The organs of vision may be affected. Burns of the skin combined with burns of the mucous membranes of the upper respiratory tract are especially dangerous. Such combinations are possible if the victim breathes hot smoke and air. This usually occurs during a fire in a closed room. Burns of the skin and mucous membranes during a fire may be combined with carbon monoxide poisoning.

Sequence of first aid for flame burns:

1. Eliminate the source of the burn. If a person's clothes catch fire, you must immediately remove them or lay the victim on his back. You can also throw a blanket, coat, bag, or overcoat over the victim, that is, cut off the air supply to the fire. Flames on clothes can be extinguished with water or covered with sand. You cannot run in burning clothes, as the wind, fanning the flames, will increase and intensify the burn. It is necessary to remove the victim from the high-temperature zone.

2. Treatment of a burn wound. When treating a wound, it is necessary to remove clothing very carefully so as not to damage the tissue even more. Moreover, if the clothing has stuck to the skin, it must not be torn off! It is necessary to carefully cut off the non-stick part of the clothing along the edges, using sharp scissors for this.

For small first-degree (redness, pain) and second-degree (severe redness, severe pain, blisters) burns, apply a sterile bandage to the burned area of skin.

In case of severe and extensive burns (more than 10% of the body surface), the victim must be wrapped in a clean sheet or cloth without undressing him, covered warmly, given warm tea to drink and kept at rest until the doctor arrives.  

When providing assistance to the victim, to avoid infection, do not touch the burned areas of the skin with your hands or lubricate them with ointments, fats, oils, petroleum jelly, sprinkle with baking soda, starch, etc. Do not open blisters, remove mastic, rosin or other resinous substances that have stuck to the burned area, since by removing them, you can easily tear off the burned skin and thereby create favorable conditions for infection of the wound. 

First aid measures for frostbite. The first stage is before the affected body part begins to warm up.

You should immediately stop the exposure to low temperatures, take the victim into a warm room or car. The main task is to gradually restore blood circulation in the affected part of the body. You should remove tight shoes and clothing that squeeze the limb and disrupt blood flow. Shoes should be removed carefully so as not to damage frostbitten toes. If this cannot be done without effort, you need to rip the boot or shoe shaft seam with a knife.

It is impossible to allow the surface layers of the skin in the affected area to warm up quickly, since the deep layers warm up more slowly. Blood flow is poorly restored in them and the upper layers of the skin do not receive enough oxygen and nutrients. As a result of nutritional deficiencies, they die. In this regard, in case of frostbite, the use of hot baths, hot air, heating pads, and hot water bottles is strictly contraindicated. Rubbing the affected areas of the body with snow is prohibited. Massage is not recommended.

A dry heat-insulating bandage, such as cotton-gauze, is applied to the frostbitten area. If this is not available, woolen fabric can be used (over cotton). When noticeable warmth appears, the bandage is removed. The affected limb must be kept at rest. To replenish the body's warmth, the victim is given hot sweet tea.

The second stage is after warming up the affected part of the body. A dry sterile bandage or one ironed with a hot iron is applied to the affected area of the body. In case of severe pain, a painkiller is given. After first aid has been provided, the victim should be taken to a medical facility as quickly as possible. During transportation, the affected limb should be immobilized (immobilized).

3. Drowning. Methods of extracting a drowning person from the water, personal safety measures. Types of drowning, features of first aid in case of true drowning

Drowning is an acute pathological condition that occurs as a result of suffocation due to accidental or intentional immersion in water.

Types of drowning. Syncopal drowning. This type of drowning is typical for the vast majority of drowned people during disasters . Syncopal drowning is characterized by primary reflex cardiac and respiratory arrest caused by even a small amount of water entering the upper respiratory tract.

A similar mechanism of development is found in the so-called “ice shock” or immersion syndrome, which develops as a result of reflex cardiac arrest during sudden immersion in cold water.

Asphyxial (dry) drowning. It can be caused by overheating in the sun, alcohol consumption, heart attack, etc. Breathing stops due to a spasm of the glottis when the first portions of water enter.

"Death on the Water". The cause of the victim's terminal condition in the water is not related to the liquid entering his respiratory tract, but to another reason (myocardial infarction, acute cerebrovascular accident, or a suddenly developing epileptic seizure).

Aspiration or "wet" drowning (or otherwise true) occurs when water enters the victim's respiratory tract and fills the lungs (75-95% of cases). Most often occurs in children and adults who cannot swim, and in people who are intoxicated.

Signs of true drowning:

  • The skin of the face and neck has a bluish tint.
  • Swelling of the vessels of the neck.
  • Profuse foamy discharge from the mouth and nose.

Methods of extracting a drowning person from water, personal safety measures. When rescuing a drowning person on the surface of the water, special care should be taken. A victim in a state of panic fear is capable of performing "dead" grips. As a result, the number of victims may increase. If there is a real threat to one's own life, it is recommended to extract the drowning person using improvised means (a stick, rope, belt), stretched from a safe distance.

Features of first aid in case of true drowning. The first thing that needs to be done is throw the drowned person face down over the rescuer's knee. The main thing is to insert two fingers into the victim's mouth as quickly as possible and remove the contents of the oral cavity with a circular motion (Fig. 22). After cleaning the oral cavity, it is necessary to press sharply on the root of the tongue to provoke a gag reflex and stimulate breathing. If the gag reflex is preserved and food remains are visible in the water pouring out of the mouth, this indicates that the person is alive. This will be confirmed by the appearance of a cough. Next, you should remove water from the stomach and lungs as thoroughly as possible for 5-10 minutes, still pressing on the base of the tongue in a face-down position. At the same time, you can pat the victim on the back with your palm, and also intensively squeeze the chest from the sides several times while inhaling.

After removing water from the upper respiratory tract, lungs and stomach, it is necessary to lay the victim on his side and call an ambulance.

Fig. 22. First aid for true drowning

If there is no gag reflex when pressing on the tongue, there are no food remnants in the flowing water, no coughing or breathing movements are observed, then cardiopulmonary resuscitation should be started immediately. To do this, the victim should be laid on his back and indirect cardiac massage should be started and artificial respiration , which every 3-4 minutes should be alternated with the removal of the contents of the mouth and nose, turning the person onto his stomach.
