Lesson 6. First aid for wounds, external bleeding, bone fractures

1. Basic rules and techniques for applying bandage dressings

Before applying the bandage, the skin around the wound must be treated with an antiseptic, and the bleeding must be stopped. Bandaging should be done carefully, without causing pain to the patient if possible. The bandage moves in one direction, each subsequent turn is slightly stretched and overlaps the previous turn by 1/3-1/2.

The most common types of bandage are sling-shaped, circular, spike-shaped, and figure-of-eight.

Sling bandage apply to the nose or chin, as well as to the entire face. The bandage is cut lengthwise at both ends, leaving the middle intact. The uncut part is applied to the wound, the ends are crossed on both sides and tied at the back (Fig. 23).

Fig. 23. Sling-like headbands

Circular bandage It is used to cover a small area of the body, such as the eye, ear, head (forehead), but it is most convenient to use it on the neck, shoulder, wrist. When applying such a P., each subsequent turn of the bandage is applied to the previous one (similar to the first turns of other bandages) (Fig. 24).

Fig. 24. Circular bandage on the wrist

Figure-of-eight (cross-shaped) bandage. Convenient for bandaging the back of the head, hand, chest, ankle joint: the bandage is fixed in circular turns, and then crossed in the shape of the number 8. In this case, all intersections occur at one point either on the flexor or extensor surface of the joints (Fig. 25).

Fig. 25. Figure-of-eight ankle bandage

Spica bandage . It is a type of cruciform bandage. Each subsequent turn of this bandage partially overlaps the previous one, pulling up the weakened bandage fabric . It is widely used for bandaging the shoulder joint, axillary region, hip joint and other hard-to-reach areas where the dressing material cannot be held in place by other methods (Fig. 26).

Fig. 26. Spica bandage on the shoulder joint

2. Features of first aid for penetrating chest wounds. First aid for spinal fractures. First aid measures for penetrating abdominal wounds.

Rules for applying a sealing (occlusal) dressings (for extensive wounds) for penetrating chest wounds:

  1. The victim must take a semi-sitting position. 
  2. A sterile napkin is applied to the wound.
  3. The next layer is made of any material that is impermeable to air (polyethylene film, oilcloth).
  4. A tight bandage is applied over the wound.

When applying a bandage, remember that each new layer of dressing material should be 5-10 cm larger than the previous one.

When bandaging open wounds in the chest cavity, a spiral bandage is used (Fig. 27)

Fig. 27. Spiral bandage on the chest

Spinal fractures in the neck and back area are very dangerous due to possible damage to the spinal cord and the development of paralysis. The victim may be in severe shock, unconscious.

The victim must be placed on a hard stretcher on his back: a piece of plywood, a shield, a door, a sled, etc. To reposition the victim, at least 5 people are needed. One is positioned at the level of the head and neck, the second - the torso, the third - the hips, the fourth - the legs. Together they lift the victim, paying attention to the fact that there is no deflection in the back and neck area. The fifth assistant places the stretcher under the victim.

Stretcher with a soft base (blankets, raincoats, etc.) are not applicable in this case due to possible deformation of the torso. When the torso sags, the axis of the spine changes and the vertebrae may shift, and if there has already been a shift, it will increase. This often leads to irreparable consequences - a rupture of the spinal cord.

If only a cloth stretcher is available, the victim should be placed on it face down, on his stomach.

First aid for abdominal wounds:

  1. You can't give him anything to drink or eat, because In case of penetrating wounds of the intestine, this accelerates the development of peritonitis (purulent inflammation of the peritoneum). To quench thirst, you can only wet your lips with water or let the victim rinse his mouth.
  2. If a person is unconscious, his head should be tilted back and

turn on your side, since this is the position in which air will be able to pass freely into the lungs, and vomit will be removed without threatening to block the airways.

3. If there is a foreign object in the wound, do not remove it under any circumstances, as this may lead to additional damage to internal organs.

4. It is necessary to fix and stabilize the object in the wound so that it does not move or shift. To do this, you can wrap the foreign object sticking out of the wound with rollers of bandages or any fabric on both sides, and then fix the entire structure with a bandage, adhesive plaster or tape.

5. In no case should the prolapsed organs be pushed back into the abdominal cavity, as this can lead to peritonitis, shock and rapid death. Rolls of bandages or cloth should be placed around the organs. Then a bandage should be applied over the rolls, without pressing or

pressing the prolapsed organs.

6. After applying a bandage or fixing the prolapsed organs, it is necessary to apply cold to the wound and wrap the victim in blankets or clothing.

7. Transport the wounded in the abdomen in a lying position with the upper part of the body raised and the legs bent at the knees. This position reduces pain and prevents the spread of the inflammatory process to all parts of the abdomen.

3. Temporary stopping of external bleeding

Digital pressure on the artery. Arteries are pressed in places where they pass near or above the bone. On the extremities, vessels are pressed above the wound, on the neck and head - below. Since the artery is mobile, the finger kind of slides off it, so it is more effective to press the artery with several fingers of one hand, tightly pressed together, or with two thumbs of both hands. When it is necessary to press a large artery (for example, the femoral), press it with a fist, and apply pressure using your own body weight. After performing finger pressure on the vessel, you should quickly apply, where possible, a tourniquet or twist and a sterile bandage to the wound (Fig. 28). 

Fig. 28. Typical places of arterial compression

Pressure bandage. A method for stopping capillary and venous bleeding is to apply a pressure bandage to the wound. Skilled application of a pressure bandage can stop bleeding even from a large arterial vessel and in anatomically complex areas.

A sterile gauze folded several times or a piece of sterile bandage is applied to the wound. This material can be moistened with hydrogen peroxide. If there is no sterile material, a pad of clean fabric (handkerchief, piece of sheet, etc.) is applied to the wound. If non-sterile dressing material is used, it is recommended to drip a little iodine tincture onto the fabric. A thick roll of bandage, cotton wool or a clean handkerchief is applied over the fabric and tightly bandaged .

An ice pack can be applied over the bandage to reduce blood flow to the injured area. Pressure bandages can be applied to almost any part of the body. A pressure bandage can be left on for up to 1.5-2 days. If the bleeding has been stopped and the pulsation below has been preserved, then the pressure bandage has been applied correctly. If the blood continues to flow and the bandage has begun to soak through again, then several more layers of gauze (bandage, napkins) should be applied on top and tightly bandaged again (Fig. 29).

Fig. 29. Application of a pressure bandage

Maximum flexion of the limb at the joint. The method is based on the maximum flexion of the limb at the joint located above wounds (as a result of which the blood vessel is compressed), and subsequent fixation of the limb in this position with a bandage, belt or other available material. A roller made of bandage or other material is first placed in the bend of the joint (a rolled-up sleeve or trouser leg can be used). Maximum flexion of the limb at the joint is used to stop arterial bleeding from the upper and lower extremities (Fig. 30). It is important to remember that this method of stopping bleeding is contraindicated in cases of soft tissue damage and bone fractures.

Fig. 30. Stopping bleeding by maximum flexion of the limb at the joint

A tourniquet is applied only in cases of significant arterial bleeding.

Application of a tourniquet (Fig. 31):

1. A cloth pad is placed under the tourniquet, which prevents possible pinching of the skin. It is permissible to apply the tourniquet directly to the wounded person's clothing.

2. The tourniquet is applied above the bleeding zone, as close as possible to the site of vessel damage.

3. The first 2 turns of the tourniquet around the limb should be the tightest.

4. Excessive tightening of the tourniquet may cause paralysis of the limb.

5. The correctness of the tourniquet application is assessed by the disappearance of the peripheral pulse or by the cessation of bleeding from the wound.

6. A note indicating the date and time of application should be placed under the tourniquet. During transportation, the area where the tourniquet was applied should not be covered with clothing.

7. The maximum time for keeping a tourniquet on adults in the warm season is up to 2 hours, in winter – up to 1 hour, and in children – up to 1 hour in the warm season and up to 30 minutes in winter. Otherwise, tissue necrosis may occur. If evacuation is delayed, it is necessary to loosen the tourniquet for 5-10 minutes, having previously pressed the artery with your fingers, and then reapply it a little higher. This is then repeated every half hour. A tourniquet should not be applied to children under three years of age.

Fig. 31. Application of a tourniquet
